WEBVTT

00:07.533 --> 00:12.433
♪♪

00:12.433 --> 00:14.233
Oh, I already know about your

00:14.233 --> 00:14.967
candidate.

00:14.967 --> 00:16.400
I know all the candidates.

00:16.400 --> 00:19.233
I'm even voting for comptroller.

00:19.233 --> 00:24.800
Wow, she's good.

00:24.800 --> 00:26.233
Get my sticker ready, George.

00:26.233 --> 00:29.567
I'm coming for it.

00:29.567 --> 00:30.233
Hi, Ms. Reem.

00:30.233 --> 00:31.567
Hi, Marie.

00:31.567 --> 00:32.433
Who are you voting for?

00:32.433 --> 00:33.600
Oh, wouldn't you like

00:33.600 --> 00:34.267
to know.

00:34.267 --> 00:35.367
You're so lucky!

00:35.367 --> 00:36.267
I have to wait six years

00:36.267 --> 00:36.933
to vote.

00:36.933 --> 00:38.067
Well, that's sooner than

00:38.067 --> 00:38.733
you think.

00:38.733 --> 00:39.767
The great thing about America

00:39.767 --> 00:42.067
is, is when your day comes,

00:42.067 --> 00:43.267
your vote will count just as

00:43.267 --> 00:45.567
much as everybody else.

00:45.567 --> 00:47.533
Huh.

00:47.533 --> 00:49.300
Okay.

00:49.300 --> 00:49.967
Actually...

00:49.967 --> 00:50.633
Aah!

00:50.633 --> 00:52.033
Some votes count way more

00:52.033 --> 00:52.700
than others.

00:52.700 --> 00:53.400
Oh, murderer!

00:53.400 --> 00:54.300
Aah, God!

00:54.300 --> 00:55.400
I'm not a murderer!

00:55.400 --> 00:56.533
I'm an Adam Conover!

00:56.533 --> 00:57.733
Oh! And this is

00:57.733 --> 00:58.800
"Adam Ruins Everything."

00:58.800 --> 00:59.467
Oh!

00:59.467 --> 01:03.100
♪♪

01:03.100 --> 01:04.567
(flame roaring)

01:04.567 --> 01:06.433
(ding-ding)

01:08.700 --> 01:10.233
Oh, jeez, I gotta stop

01:10.233 --> 01:11.233
surprising people.

01:11.233 --> 01:13.100
I waste so much milk.

01:13.100 --> 01:14.533
Mr. Conover, I'm trying

01:14.533 --> 01:15.200
to vote.

01:15.200 --> 01:16.633
The voting booth is a sacred

01:16.633 --> 01:18.867
space, now get out of here!

01:18.867 --> 01:20.233
Actually, despite our best

01:20.233 --> 01:22.133
intentions, our system is way

01:22.133 --> 01:23.800
less democratic than we think.

01:23.800 --> 01:24.800
That is not true.

01:24.800 --> 01:26.533
I love our democracy.

01:26.533 --> 01:28.533
So do I, but it has some room

01:28.533 --> 01:29.300
for improvement.

01:29.300 --> 01:30.600
You want me to show you?

01:30.600 --> 01:32.767
Eh, go ahead, kiddo.

01:32.767 --> 01:34.100
Okay! Ah.

01:34.100 --> 01:36.800
This is a map of America.

01:36.800 --> 01:37.467
Is it?

01:37.467 --> 01:39.067
It looks like a dying turkey.

01:39.067 --> 01:39.767
Ugh, yeah.

01:39.767 --> 01:41.733
I have poor fine motor skills.

01:41.733 --> 01:42.733
Here, give me that.

01:42.733 --> 01:43.400
Oh.

01:43.400 --> 01:44.900
I teach drawing at the

01:44.900 --> 01:45.900
learning annex.

01:45.900 --> 01:48.067
Hmm.

01:48.067 --> 01:49.200
Mm-hmm.

01:49.200 --> 01:50.600
Wow, thank you, Donna.

01:50.600 --> 01:52.933
Now, so, every four years, we

01:52.933 --> 01:54.467
hear the words "electoral

01:54.467 --> 01:56.233
college" over and over again.

01:56.233 --> 01:57.400
But, we never talk about what

01:57.400 --> 01:59.033
a ridiculous and, frankly,

01:59.033 --> 02:00.433
undemocratic system it

02:00.433 --> 02:01.200
really is.

02:01.200 --> 02:02.633
The electoral college gives

02:02.633 --> 02:04.467
vastly more power to different

02:04.467 --> 02:05.733
voters, depending on which state

02:05.733 --> 02:06.567
they live in.

02:06.567 --> 02:07.733
Bigger states?

02:07.733 --> 02:08.967
Nope, smaller states.

02:08.967 --> 02:10.767
If your state has less people,

02:10.767 --> 02:12.567
you have more power.

02:12.567 --> 02:13.667
Not too many people live in

02:13.700 --> 02:15.067
Wyoming, but they have three

02:15.067 --> 02:16.733
electoral votes, or one for

02:16.733 --> 02:19.433
every 135,000 voters.

02:19.433 --> 02:20.767
California is packed with

02:20.767 --> 02:22.800
people, but they have 55

02:22.800 --> 02:24.533
electoral votes, or one for

02:24.533 --> 02:26.933
every 411,000 voters.

02:26.933 --> 02:27.800
And that's totally out of

02:27.800 --> 02:28.900
proportion, because it means it

02:28.900 --> 02:30.267
takes three times as many

02:30.267 --> 02:31.900
Californians to earn one

02:31.900 --> 02:33.733
electoral vote, giving voters in

02:33.733 --> 02:35.567
Wyoming three times the power in

02:35.567 --> 02:36.900
the electoral college.

02:36.900 --> 02:38.533
As a result of this system, your

02:38.533 --> 02:40.033
vote could count for less just

02:40.067 --> 02:42.067
because of where you live.

02:42.067 --> 02:43.867
Infographics rule, right?

02:43.867 --> 02:45.067
Yeah, well, it does seem

02:45.067 --> 02:46.533
unfair, but who cares if the

02:46.533 --> 02:48.133
electoral college is kooky?

02:48.133 --> 02:48.800
I'm kooky.

02:48.800 --> 02:49.800
I have two turtles.

02:49.800 --> 02:51.100
Okay, well, it gets worse,

02:51.100 --> 02:52.567
because the electoral college

02:52.567 --> 02:54.700
also creates swing states.

02:54.700 --> 02:56.400
Oh, I love the swing states!

02:56.400 --> 02:57.633
They make election night so

02:57.633 --> 02:58.900
exciting, kind of like when my

02:58.900 --> 03:00.400
turtles move a little.

03:00.400 --> 03:01.700
Wha-- Exciting?

03:01.700 --> 03:03.067
I think the fact that the entire

03:03.067 --> 03:04.267
election is determined by just

03:04.267 --> 03:06.300
a handful of states is really

03:06.300 --> 03:07.033
messed up.

03:07.033 --> 03:08.067
For one thing, it means

03:08.067 --> 03:09.267
presidential candidates can

03:09.267 --> 03:10.900
ignore almost the entire

03:10.900 --> 03:12.867
country.

03:12.867 --> 03:13.867
Hello, America.

03:13.867 --> 03:15.367
I'm Adam Conover, and I'm

03:15.367 --> 03:16.367
running for president of

03:16.367 --> 03:18.900
Florida, Pennsylvania, and Ohio.

03:18.900 --> 03:20.567
And, boy, do I love Florida

03:20.567 --> 03:22.033
oranges, Philadelphia

03:22.033 --> 03:23.800
cheesesteaks, and whatever you

03:23.800 --> 03:25.233
people like in Ohio.

03:25.233 --> 03:25.900
Eh.

03:25.900 --> 03:26.667
The rest of the country can go

03:26.700 --> 03:28.767
suck a big one.

03:28.767 --> 03:29.767
People in Ohio like

03:29.800 --> 03:30.800
LeBron James.

03:30.800 --> 03:31.567
Who?

03:31.567 --> 03:32.700
I don't know many actors.

03:32.700 --> 03:34.567
Anyway, swing states have so

03:34.567 --> 03:36.067
much power that in recent

03:36.067 --> 03:38.767
elections, up to 80% of all the

03:38.767 --> 03:40.700
votes cast in America had no

03:40.700 --> 03:42.233
impact on the outcome.

03:42.233 --> 03:43.433
That includes your vote here in

03:43.433 --> 03:44.300
California.

03:44.300 --> 03:45.267
Well, some states are red

03:45.267 --> 03:46.700
states, and some states are blue

03:46.700 --> 03:47.367
states.

03:47.367 --> 03:48.800
That's the way America is.

03:48.800 --> 03:50.533
Actually, most states are

03:50.533 --> 03:51.200
pretty purple.

03:51.200 --> 03:55.467
♪♪

03:55.467 --> 03:58.400
In 2012, over 3 million Texans

03:58.400 --> 03:59.567
voted Democrat.

03:59.567 --> 04:00.767
I love barbecue, Blake

04:00.767 --> 04:02.567
Shelton, and abortions, y'all.

04:02.567 --> 04:03.967
And almost 5 million

04:03.967 --> 04:06.067
Californians voted Republican.

04:06.067 --> 04:07.233
Surf's up, y'all.

04:07.233 --> 04:07.900
You know what else needs to

04:07.900 --> 04:08.567
go up?

04:08.567 --> 04:10.733
Border wall with Mexico, dude.

04:10.733 --> 04:11.400
(chuckling)

04:11.400 --> 04:12.400
If electoral votes were

04:12.400 --> 04:13.600
awarded proportionately,

04:13.600 --> 04:16.567
in 2012, 16 of Texas's electoral

04:16.567 --> 04:18.067
votes would have gone to Obama,

04:18.067 --> 04:19.933
and 20 of California's would

04:19.933 --> 04:21.300
have gone to Romney.

04:21.300 --> 04:22.400
But in our winner-take-all

04:22.400 --> 04:23.733
system, anyone who wants to vote

04:23.733 --> 04:25.233
for their state's losing party

04:25.233 --> 04:26.600
might as well just stay home.

04:26.600 --> 04:27.900
Oh, bummer!

04:27.900 --> 04:29.567
Okay, everybody, get out!

04:29.567 --> 04:31.900
I can't listen to any more!

04:31.900 --> 04:32.967
How about we all vote?

04:32.967 --> 04:33.933
Wait, who are all these

04:33.933 --> 04:34.600
people?

04:34.600 --> 04:36.067
Oh, these are the electors.

04:36.067 --> 04:37.600
They're the people who actually

04:37.600 --> 04:38.733
vote for president.

04:38.733 --> 04:39.767
I thought the electoral

04:39.767 --> 04:41.100
college was just a name.

04:41.100 --> 04:42.067
Oh, nope!

04:42.067 --> 04:43.467
When we vote, we're actually

04:43.467 --> 04:44.600
just picking our state's

04:44.600 --> 04:45.533
electors.

04:45.567 --> 04:46.400
Then, those electors get

04:46.400 --> 04:48.067
together and cast their ballots

04:48.067 --> 04:49.567
for president.

04:49.567 --> 04:51.200
But, who are they?

04:51.233 --> 04:52.733
Oh, mostly retired

04:52.733 --> 04:54.267
politicians and party flaks.

04:54.267 --> 04:55.633
(laughing)

04:55.633 --> 04:57.400
I'm the governor's rich cousin.

04:57.400 --> 04:59.733
Okay, Mr. Smarty, that's just

04:59.733 --> 05:00.900
a technicality.

05:00.900 --> 05:02.233
They have to vote for who

05:02.233 --> 05:03.467
we choose.

05:03.467 --> 05:05.533
Actually, in 24 states,

05:05.533 --> 05:07.033
they can vote for whoever

05:07.067 --> 05:09.200
they want.

05:09.233 --> 05:10.600
And that's happened over

05:10.600 --> 05:11.800
80 times.

05:11.800 --> 05:14.267
In 2004, an elector in Minnesota

05:14.267 --> 05:16.200
cast his vote for someone named

05:16.233 --> 05:18.867
"John Ewards"... which was

05:18.867 --> 05:20.600
almost the name of John Kerry's

05:20.600 --> 05:21.533
running mate.

05:21.567 --> 05:23.100
Did you mean "John Edwards"?

05:23.100 --> 05:24.600
Yes. (chuckling)

05:24.600 --> 05:27.967
I may have a drinking problem.

05:27.967 --> 05:29.300
That actually happened?

05:29.300 --> 05:31.067
That actually happened.

05:31.067 --> 05:32.700
That elector's vote didn't go to

05:32.700 --> 05:33.467
John Kerry.

05:33.467 --> 05:35.067
It went to the guy running for

05:35.067 --> 05:36.400
vice-president.

05:36.400 --> 05:37.733
The electoral college is such

05:37.733 --> 05:39.133
a bad system, people have been

05:39.133 --> 05:40.067
trying to abolish it for

05:40.067 --> 05:40.733
centuries...

05:40.733 --> 05:41.400
Oh.

05:41.400 --> 05:42.100
But, so far, it's been

05:42.100 --> 05:43.567
politically impossible.

05:43.567 --> 05:44.633
Okay, well, thank you for the

05:44.633 --> 05:45.433
information.

05:45.433 --> 05:46.867
I cannot believe our beautiful

05:46.867 --> 05:49.367
system has become so messed up.

05:49.367 --> 05:50.767
Oh, no, the founding fathers

05:50.767 --> 05:51.900
designed our system this

05:51.900 --> 05:53.233
messed up. (chuckling)

05:53.233 --> 05:54.900
All right, hold on a minute,

05:54.900 --> 05:55.800
young man.

05:55.800 --> 05:57.067
You do not talk about the

05:57.067 --> 05:58.733
founding fathers like that.

05:58.733 --> 06:00.200
They were brilliant men, who

06:00.200 --> 06:01.233
fought hard for my right

06:01.233 --> 06:01.933
to vote.

06:01.933 --> 06:02.900
Actually, the founding

06:02.900 --> 06:03.967
fathers didn't think you should

06:03.967 --> 06:05.033
be able to vote at all.

06:05.033 --> 06:05.967
Or me.

06:05.967 --> 06:08.067
Or most Americans. (chuckling)

06:08.067 --> 06:10.067
Let's go back in time, and I'll

06:10.067 --> 06:10.767
prove it to you.

06:10.767 --> 06:12.800
(console beeping)

06:12.800 --> 06:15.400
Oh... those are single-use.

06:15.400 --> 06:18.100
Aah!

06:18.100 --> 06:19.100
(whistling)

06:22.400 --> 06:25.067
(energy crackling)

06:25.100 --> 06:26.233
Donna, welcome to

06:26.233 --> 06:29.000
Philadelphia, 1787.

06:29.033 --> 06:30.400
My gosh, this is like a dream

06:30.400 --> 06:31.300
vacation.

06:31.300 --> 06:33.400
Oh! There's James Madison, and

06:33.400 --> 06:35.600
Alexander Hamilton.

06:35.600 --> 06:37.300
Ew, what-- what's that smell?

06:37.300 --> 06:37.967
(sniffing)

06:37.967 --> 06:39.133
Well, it's probably the

06:39.133 --> 06:40.567
chamber pots.

06:40.567 --> 06:41.433
And this is...?

06:41.433 --> 06:42.567
Oh, hey, Ed!

06:42.567 --> 06:44.267
Uh, Donna, this is Ed Ayers.

06:44.300 --> 06:44.967
He's a historian at the

06:44.967 --> 06:46.100
University of Richmond.

06:46.100 --> 06:46.933
He's just back here doing

06:46.967 --> 06:47.733
a little research.

06:47.733 --> 06:48.467
So, you brought us somebody

06:48.467 --> 06:49.733
else to introduce to the

06:49.733 --> 06:50.633
founding fathers' era?

06:50.633 --> 06:51.533
Yeah, you want to tell her

06:51.533 --> 06:52.300
about 'em?

06:52.300 --> 06:52.967
The story is a little

06:52.967 --> 06:53.767
discouraging.

06:53.767 --> 06:55.433
We revere the founding fathers,

06:55.433 --> 06:57.200
as we should, but their ideas of

06:57.200 --> 06:58.733
democracy were just a little bit

06:58.733 --> 06:59.800
different from ours.

06:59.800 --> 07:01.400
Oh, I cannot believe that.

07:01.400 --> 07:02.800
Oh, well, see for yourself.

07:02.800 --> 07:03.467
They're creating our election

07:03.467 --> 07:04.133
system.

07:04.133 --> 07:04.800
(gavel banging)

07:04.800 --> 07:06.233
Gentlemen, I submit to you,

07:06.233 --> 07:08.133
good sirs, that we structure

07:08.133 --> 07:12.100
America as a direct democracy,

07:12.100 --> 07:13.900
one where every person votes

07:13.900 --> 07:16.467
directly for president.

07:16.467 --> 07:17.967
(Donna clapping alone)

07:17.967 --> 07:19.100
Psych!

07:19.100 --> 07:20.467
J/K, boys!

07:20.467 --> 07:22.133
That would be ridiculous!

07:22.133 --> 07:23.367
(laughter)

07:23.367 --> 07:25.033
That-- that can't be!

07:25.033 --> 07:26.367
Adams, you believed it.

07:26.367 --> 07:27.033
You believed it!

07:27.033 --> 07:27.700
I saw your face!

07:27.700 --> 07:28.633
Why didn't they want direct

07:28.633 --> 07:29.633
democracy?

07:29.633 --> 07:30.300
Honestly?

07:30.300 --> 07:31.933
They didn't trust us to vote

07:31.933 --> 07:32.600
correctly.

07:32.600 --> 07:34.267
Put yourself in their shoes.

07:34.267 --> 07:35.400
They're creating a new country.

07:35.400 --> 07:36.300
They're not sure what's gonna

07:36.300 --> 07:37.033
happen.

07:37.033 --> 07:37.867
They're kind of worried about

07:37.867 --> 07:39.233
too much democracy, and they

07:39.233 --> 07:40.300
think it's be a good idea,

07:40.300 --> 07:41.800
maybe, for there to be a buffer

07:41.800 --> 07:43.100
between the people and the

07:43.100 --> 07:43.767
government.

07:43.767 --> 07:45.533
The common man could vote for

07:45.533 --> 07:47.033
the king of England, or a

07:47.033 --> 07:49.967
demagogue, or, like, little bugs

07:49.967 --> 07:50.633
or something.

07:50.633 --> 07:51.300
I don't know.

07:51.300 --> 07:53.300
They're very, very dumb people.

07:53.300 --> 07:55.633
How about, we have the people

07:55.633 --> 07:58.633
choose electors, and then they

07:58.633 --> 07:59.767
pick the president?

07:59.767 --> 08:01.867
Like, I don't know, the

08:01.867 --> 08:02.733
governor's rich cousin can

08:02.733 --> 08:03.400
do it.

08:03.400 --> 08:04.567
Oh, how condescending.

08:04.567 --> 08:06.133
Yeah, they kind of were.

08:06.133 --> 08:07.567
And, there was one particular

08:07.567 --> 08:08.867
group of states that rallied

08:08.867 --> 08:10.233
really hard against direct

08:10.233 --> 08:11.033
democracy.

08:11.033 --> 08:12.467
The smaller states?

08:12.467 --> 08:13.300
Not quite.

08:13.300 --> 08:15.033
Yeah, y'all, it would be

08:15.033 --> 08:16.533
great for us to have

08:16.533 --> 08:18.600
representative democracy that

08:18.600 --> 08:20.300
gave us credit for the

08:20.300 --> 08:23.467
population of our states.

08:23.467 --> 08:24.800
Even if some of those people

08:24.800 --> 08:26.533
aren't actually voting, if you,

08:26.533 --> 08:28.433
uh, catch my meaning.

08:28.433 --> 08:30.533
(coughing) Slaves!

08:30.533 --> 08:32.133
He's talking about slaves!

08:32.133 --> 08:33.633
Are you saying the slave states

08:33.633 --> 08:34.600
are responsible for the

08:34.600 --> 08:35.867
electoral college?

08:35.867 --> 08:37.067
Well, to a considerable

08:37.067 --> 08:38.067
extent.

08:38.067 --> 08:39.933
Slave states were very powerful.

08:39.933 --> 08:41.267
If you're gonna have a "United"

08:41.267 --> 08:42.633
States, you're gonna have to

08:42.633 --> 08:43.633
make concessions to bring

08:43.633 --> 08:44.367
them in.

08:44.367 --> 08:45.567
Yeah, look, the founding

08:45.567 --> 08:46.800
fathers weren't benevolent

08:46.800 --> 08:47.600
demigods.

08:47.600 --> 08:48.800
They were humans who made

08:48.800 --> 08:50.433
compromises and mistakes.

08:50.433 --> 08:51.767
And building a compromise with

08:51.767 --> 08:53.300
slavery into the structure of

08:53.300 --> 08:55.433
our government was one of them.

08:55.433 --> 08:56.467
Would you excuse me for just

08:56.467 --> 08:57.133
a minute?

08:57.133 --> 08:57.967
Sure.

08:57.967 --> 09:00.400
Mr. Conover, that is enough.

09:00.400 --> 09:02.367
I may not know everything, but

09:02.367 --> 09:03.900
I passionately believe that

09:03.900 --> 09:06.200
reading is fundamental, and that

09:06.200 --> 09:07.867
Gordon Ramsay's wit is

09:07.867 --> 09:10.033
underappreciated, and that even

09:10.033 --> 09:12.067
though the founding fathers may

09:12.067 --> 09:13.967
not have been perfect, they are

09:13.967 --> 09:16.867
still noble and brave men who

09:16.867 --> 09:19.367
believed that every citizen has

09:19.367 --> 09:23.133
a right to vote, so help me God.

09:23.133 --> 09:24.133
Oh, no, they didn't think

09:24.133 --> 09:25.033
that you should be able to vote

09:25.033 --> 09:26.267
at all.

09:26.267 --> 09:28.133
Right, because I'm a woman.

09:28.133 --> 09:29.600
Oh, no, because you don't

09:29.600 --> 09:30.300
own land.

09:30.300 --> 09:31.433
Also, because you're a woman.

09:31.433 --> 09:32.300
Yeah.

09:32.300 --> 09:35.867
All men are created equal...

09:35.867 --> 09:37.633
if they have land.

09:37.633 --> 09:38.467
Like this guy.

09:38.467 --> 09:39.267
He owns a farm.

09:39.267 --> 09:40.433
He's equal to me.

09:40.433 --> 09:41.967
Not so much, the rest of you.

09:41.967 --> 09:43.700
You're... not quite people.

09:43.700 --> 09:46.267
Whoo, farm boys for life!

09:46.267 --> 09:48.133
Farmers only! Get!

